Small Business Mythology vs US Business Data

Pawel Rzeczkowski

2022-12-28

Abstract

It is almost impossible to live in the USA and not be subjected to some version of the mythology that small business is the heartbeat of the US economy.

Given that business concentration in US is not evenly distributed across all states, some of the messaging is politicians pandering to small businesses for support, endorsements and campaign contributions.

Another source of bias comes from enterprises catering their services to small businesses, thus leaning in with patronizing language to support the popular small business mythology. A case and point would be a small business lender.

My lived experiance does not corroborate the Small Business mythology. Below is a table dividing what I might purchase from small vs big businesses:

Big Business Provides

  • Clothing
  • Hygiene products
  • Electronics
  • Financial products
  • Transportation
  • Condiments
  • Soft drinks
  • Supermarkets where I buy all of this

Small Business Provides

  • Gardner
  • Kids nanny
  • Hairdresser
  • Massage therapist

Faced with this dissonance of public messaging versus my lived experiance, I crave real hardcore data to shed light on the composition of business in the USA.

I found that no matter how many stories about Small Business warm your heart, the data provided by government statistics on all US businesses does not support the small business mythology.

What follows is a detailed look at the public data on US business. If you are not interested in the data preparation and cleaning, feel free to jump down to the Analysis section.

Support

Luckily we do not have to rely on mythology to interpret our world. The big business that is our government collects and publishes volumes of data.

Statistics of U.S. Businesses (SUSB) is an annual series that provides national and sub-national data on the distribution of economic data by establishment industry & enterprise size. It is based on this data that people distinguish between small business, employing less than 500 people or big business, employing 500 or more people.

To do the analysis I used the latest available year, 2019.

If you want to follow along the data analysis, download the U.S. & states, 6 digit NAICS (50.3 MB) comma delimited text file. This is 568,330 rows across 14 columns of business data.

Import the 50.3 MB text file you downloaded from the government link I provided and load the us_state_6digitnaics_2019 table. For ease of use, I converted this file to csv format.

SBA2019 <- read.csv("/Users/pawelrzeczkowski/Google Drive/Goggle Certificate/Portfolio Projects/SBA Job Creators/us_state_6digitnaics_2019.csv", 
                      header=TRUE, fileEncoding = "UTF-8")

Now it’s time to clean up some data.

The government issued table contains multiple levels of summaries along three distinct hierarchies. In order to analyse the data, we need to strip out all the summaries.

Enterprise Employment Size Description is one of the fields with summaries. The business census data is organized by how many people the enterprise employs: * <5 * 5-9 * 10-19 * 20-99 * 100-499 * 500+

On top of those basic groupings three summaries are included in the data: * Total * <20 * <500

Let’s eliminate the summaries.

SBA2019 <- SBA2019[which(SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR != "05: <20"), ]
SBA2019 <- SBA2019[which(SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR != "08: <500"),]
SBA2019 <- SBA2019[which(SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR != "01: Total"),]

Besides the States detail being provided for the businesses location, the data includes a summary for the United States. Let’s eliminate that.

SBA2019 <- SBA2019[SBA2019$STATEDSCR != "United States",]

Finally, we have the NAICS or Industry classification hierarchy. At the highest level of the hierarchy the industries are represented with a two-digit classification code. At the lowest level of the hierarchy the industry detail is represented with a six digit code.

I have tested the accuracy of the two-digit level detail vs the six-digit level detail and the two-digit detail is more accurate vs the government provided summaries. Perhaps this discrepancy is where the good enough for government work moniker comes from. The detail does not roll up exactly to the provided summaries. This will not impact this analysis as the 4% difference on number of firms is not material to the result. At the two-digit hierarchy level, the payroll and employee data are consistent with the summary level provided, thus I used the two-digit summary level for industry breakout.

Let’s eliminate the industry summaries first.

            SBA2019 <- SBA2019[SBA2019$NAICSDSCR != "Total",]

Getting to a clean two-digit level summary is slightly complicated by presentation groupings of industries such as 31-33 Manufacturing, 44-45 Retail Trade and 48-49 Transportation and Warehousing.

I made a copy of the field with the hierarchy listing. Next I isolated the 3rd character. If the character is a dash “-” that means it is two-digit grouping and if the character is a space, it means it is a two-digit grouping. I eliminated all other records.

SBA2019$NAICSmix <- SBA2019$NAICS
SBA2019$NAICSmix <- substr(SBA2019$NAICSmix, start = 3, stop = 3)
SBA2019$NAICSmix[SBA2019$NAICSmix == ""] <- "ThisOne"
SBA2019$NAICSmix[SBA2019$NAICSmix == "-"] <- "ThisOne"
SBA2019 <- SBA2019[SBA2019$NAICSmix == "ThisOne",]
SBA2019$NAICSmix <- NULL

Let’s do a quick check to see how the data detail I extracted from the table compares to the government provided summary. I divided the summary of the detail by the provided summary.

              SBA2019 %>% summarize(Employees = (sum(EMPL)/132000000)*100,
                                Payroll = (sum(PAYR)/7428553593)*100,
                                Firms = (sum(FIRM)/6102412)*100) %>%
              mutate_if(is.numeric, round, digits=1)
##   Employees Payroll Firms
## 1     100.7     100 104.6

Almost 100 percent across the board,thus, we will call this close enough for government work. If you know someone at the census bureau, let them know their statistics are slightly off, or let me know what I am doing wrong.

Now we need a little cosmetic work on the table.

In order to create a stacked bar graph breaking out the composition of the various firm sizes that make up the small business in USA, I need a field that only classifies records as: * Small Business or Enterprise with less than 500 employees on average * Big Business or Enterprise with more than 500 employees on average

I created such column:

SBA2019$ENTR_SUM <- SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR
SBA2019$ENTR_SUM[SBA2019$ENTR_SUM == "02: <5"] <- "<500"
SBA2019$ENTR_SUM[SBA2019$ENTR_SUM == "03: 5-9"] <- "<500"
SBA2019$ENTR_SUM[SBA2019$ENTR_SUM == "04: 10-19"] <- "<500"
SBA2019$ENTR_SUM[SBA2019$ENTR_SUM == "06: 20-99"] <- "<500"
SBA2019$ENTR_SUM[SBA2019$ENTR_SUM == "07: 100-499"] <- "<500"
SBA2019$ENTR_SUM[SBA2019$ENTR_SUM == "09: 500+"] <- "500+"

Since I want to graph using the Enterprise size buckets and I deleted several that were redundant groupings, I cleaned up the order of the bucket descriptions.

SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR[SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR == "02: <5"] <- "01: <5"
SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR[SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR == "03: 5-9"] <- "02: 5-9"
SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR[SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR == "04: 10-19"] <- "03: 10-19"
SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR[SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR == "06: 20-99"] <- "04: 20-99"
SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR[SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR == "07: 100-499"] <- "05: 100-499"
SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR[SBA2019$ENTRSIZEDSCR == "09: 500+"] <- "06: 500+"

I want to look at the relationship between firm size and employee pay. To do that I need to add two calculated fields. One is average employees per firm and the other is average salary per employee. I added those.

SBA2019$EMPL_FIRM <-SBA2019$EMPL /SBA2019$FIRM
SBA2019$PAY_EMPL <-SBA2019$PAYR /SBA2019$EMPL

Finally for clarity, I made some of the column names more meaningful.

colnames(SBA2019)[colnames(SBA2019) == "STATE"] <- "STATE_No"
colnames(SBA2019)[colnames(SBA2019) == "STATEDSCR"] <- "STATE"
colnames(SBA2019)[colnames(SBA2019) == "PAYR"] <- "ANNUAL_PAY"
colnames(SBA2019)[colnames(SBA2019) == "FIRM"] <- "FIRMS"
colnames(SBA2019)[colnames(SBA2019) == "NAICSDSCR"] <- "INDUSTRY"
colnames(SBA2019)[colnames(SBA2019) == "ENTRSIZEDSCR"] <- "Business_Size"

This will do it for the cleaning and manipulation of the data. Now let’s look at the data.

Analysis

US Census Bureau classifies small businesses as those under 500 employees. Big business is any business that has more than 500 employees. For simplicity, I’ll only look at the employee based classification. Another classification option is by revenue, however, that varies by industry.

Majority of The Businesses Are Small Businesses

We have a strong expectation that overwhelming majority of US businesses are small businesses. Let’s take a look at the number of firms by business size.

              ggplot(data=SBA2019[SBA2019$PAY_EMPL < 250,], 
                   aes(ENTR_SUM, FIRMS, fill=Business_Size)) + 
              geom_bar(stat = "summary", fun = "sum") +
              labs(title = "Firm Count By Business Size",
                   subtitle = "Small vs Big Business (by No of Employees)",
                   x = "Business Size",
                   y = "Number of Firms",
                   color = "Region") +
              theme_fivethirtyeight() +
              theme(axis.title = element_text()) +
              scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
              scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::unit_format(suffix = ""))

This is an expected result.

More of us Work for Big Businesses

Here we get bit of the reality and scale of big businesses. It is a fitting name as it turns out more of us work for big business than for small business, even though big business represents less than 1% of the businesses in USA.

              ggplot(data=SBA2019[SBA2019$PAY_EMPL < 250,], 
                   aes(ENTR_SUM, EMPL, fill=Business_Size)) + 
              geom_bar(stat = "summary", fun = "sum") +
              labs(title = "Employee Count By Business Size",
                   subtitle = "Small vs Big Business (by No of Employees)",
                   x = "Business Size",
                   y = "Number of Emplyees",
                   color = "Region") +
              theme_fivethirtyeight() +
              theme(axis.title = element_text()) +
              scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
              scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::unit_format(suffix = ""))

In Agregate Big Business Pays us More

Let’s forget for a moment that salary is not a comprehensive metric of compensation as executives get paid with equity, and all of us worker bees hope to benefit from some medical and 401K benefits. For simplicity we will just look at the data we have which is salary only.

Let’s be generous to the small business myth and lets say that we are roughly split 50/50. About half of us works for small business and the other half for big business. However, when we add up all the salaries, the answer is clear. Big business pays more.

              ggplot(data=SBA2019[SBA2019$PAY_EMPL < 250,], 
                   aes(ENTR_SUM, ANNUAL_PAY, fill=Business_Size)) + 
              geom_bar(stat = "summary", fun = "sum") +
              labs(title = "Annual Pay By Business Size",
                   subtitle = "Small vs Big Business (by No of Employees)",
                   x = "Business Size",
                   y = "Total Annual Payrol",
                   color = "Region") +
              theme_fivethirtyeight() +
              theme(axis.title = element_text()) +
              scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
              scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::dollar_format())

Howaver, you scratch your head and say:“Wait a minute! What about all the highly compensated big business executives? Are they not skewing the numbers?” Well, the biggest part of their comp is likely not included in the census bureau salary statistics. Though lets look at the data by employee.

Bigger Business Bigger Pay Per Employee

Let’s look for a relationship between the average pay and business size.

              ggplot(data=SBA2019[SBA2019$PAY_EMPL < 250,]) +
              geom_point(mapping=aes(x=EMPL_FIRM, y=PAY_EMPL, color = NAICS)) +
              labs(title = "Employee Pay vs Firm Size",
                   subtitle = "By Industry Type",
                   x = "Average No of Employees per Firm",
                   y = "Average Annual Employee Pay",
                   color = "Industry Type") +
              theme_fivethirtyeight() +
              theme(axis.title = element_text()) +
              scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
              scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::dollar_format(suffix = "K")) +
              scale_x_continuous(labels=scales::unit_format(suffix = ""))

The colors represent industry classifications. Diving into the specific industries would be fascinating, but that’s a topic for another analysis.

I am interested if in general the average salaries have a positive relationship with the business size. Let’s add a trend line for all the various industries.

              ggplot(data=SBA2019[SBA2019$PAY_EMPL < 250,]) +
              geom_point(mapping=aes(x=EMPL_FIRM, y=PAY_EMPL, color = NAICS)) +
              geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=EMPL_FIRM, y=PAY_EMPL, color=NAICS, 
                                      alpha= 0.2), alpha= 0.2) +
              labs(title = "Employee Pay vs Firm Size",
                   subtitle = "By Industry Type",
                   x = "Average No of Employees per Firm",
                   y = "Average Annual Employee Pay",
                   color = "Industry Type") +
              theme_fivethirtyeight() +
              theme(axis.title = element_text()) +
              scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
              scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::dollar_format(suffix = "K")) +
              scale_x_continuous(labels=scales::unit_format(suffix = ""))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Obviously, results vary by industry, although overall the average salary tends to increase or stay flat as the size of the business grows. But let’s take a look at average salaries for big and small business.

            SB <- SBA2019[SBA2019$ENTR_SUM == "<500",]
            BB <- SBA2019[SBA2019$ENTR_SUM == "500+",]
            Total <- sum(SBA2019$ANNUAL_PAY)/sum(SBA2019$EMPL)
            Big_Business <- sum(BB$ANNUAL_PAY)/sum(BB$EMPL)
            Smal_Business <- sum(SB$ANNUAL_PAY)/sum(SB$EMPL)
            PAY_MORE <- data.table(Smal_Business, Big_Business)
            
            ggplot(data = NULL, aes(x = names(PAY_MORE), y = as.numeric(PAY_MORE)*1000)) +
              geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill=as.character(PAY_MORE))) +
              labs(title = "Average Annual Pay Per Employee",
                   subtitle = "Salary Only",
                   x = "Business Size",
                   y = "Average Pay",
                   color = "Region") +
              geom_text(aes(label = dollar(as.numeric(PAY_MORE)*1000)), 
                        position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 9)+
              theme_minimal() +
              theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),legend.position = "none",
                    plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold")) +
              scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
              scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::dollar_format())

Thus, based on the Census Bureau Statistics of U.S. Businesses, we can confirm with some authority that the notion that small business is the heartbeat or main driver of US economy is a myth. We need to look closer at the motivation of the politicians or businesses perpetuating this myth to grasp their incentives.

The data shows clearly that:

  • More of us work for big businesses.
  • Those of us who work for big businesses:
    • tend to make more money in aggregate,
    • and on average as individuals.

If we accept that consumer spending is an engine for U.S. job growth than we must acknowledge that big business creates financially healthier consumers and by extension healthier economy. Dare I say consumers are the heartbeat of the US economy, if I follow the data, significantly more money in aggregate is brought in by consumers who work at big businesses. Feel free to reach out if you have any questions or comments on that.

Context for The Additional Analysis Ideas

Apple, Amazon, Google, Hewlett-Packard, or Microsoft, are but a handful of companies that started out in a garage. For the last few years the FANGs market capitalization dominated the public exchanges. Such companies animate every Venture Capitalists wet dreams. The graph of the number of big vs small businesses underscores how rare such growth is. To translate this to mainstream speak, your garage band has more of a chance being struck by lightning than becoming U2. Don’t trust me, ask ChatGPT.

Juxtaposing the small business mythology vs the big business dominance reality founded in the data, my curiosity wonders into the cultural and regulatory environment that reflexively is the fertile soil out of which our business structures emerge. If the small business pandering is happening among the members of the legislative body settling laws in our society, the analysis of that might be few notches above my pay grade as an analyst.

It is also important to note that the data annualized is historical. We are looking into the rear-view mirror. However, as our economy transforms into the network economy model, it would be interesting to analyze the platforms dependencies and how that changes the structural reality of business competitiveness and composition in our economy. I am referring not just to the dependencies of influencers and the corporate advertising budgets that power them on platforms but also on the shift the tech drives from transaction to relationship and how that changes the business landscape.

Finally, the first graph I showed you was of the number of businesses by business size. The light blue area dominates that small business bar, the only bar standing. That is 60% of US businesses employ five employees or less. It would be interesting to dive deeper into that big pool of “businesses”. If we look at the average employees per business in that group that number is only 1.6. Yes, only 1.6 people work on average at 60% of the businesses in US. That would explain why businesses classified as employees less than 5 employees represent only 10% of the workforce. My curiosity immediately goes to who might that be? Solo asset manager? My hairdresser? The plumber? or a highly educated independent consultant who worked at the bulge bracket big firms and struck on their own. But all such relationships and the tax code they live in is topic for another analysis.

This simple analysis raises a million more questions than it answers. Hope you enjoyed it as much as I did.
